          "text": "# Task: Research and Improve Ember Threat Model\n\n## Context\n\nYou are working on **Ember** (https://github.com/leon0399/ember), a Rust-based, end-to-end encrypted, delay-tolerant networking (DTN) messenger. The current threat model document (`docs/drafts/threat-model.md`) covers only LAN discovery scenarios. It needs to be expanded into a comprehensive system-level threat model covering all protocol components.\n\n## Reference documents\n\nRead these before starting:\n\n1. `docs/drafts/threat-model.md` — current threat model (LAN discovery only)\n2. `docs/drafts/WHITEPAPER.md` — full protocol specification (especially §3.2 threat model, §7 crypto design, §8 wire format, §9 DAG, §10 tombstones, §11 transport, §12 security analysis)\n3. `docs/drafts/session-encryption.md` — Noise XX session encryption spec (especially field authentication table, replay protection, key lifecycle)\n4. `docs/drafts/merkle-dag.md` — DAG ordering and gap detection\n5. `docs/drafts/tiered-delivery.md` — three-phase delivery state machine, quorum semantics\n6. `docs/drafts/lan-discovery.md` — LAN discovery architecture\n7. `ROADMAP.md` — version plan and feature status\n\n## Research phase\n\nBefore writing, research the codebase to ground the threat analysis in actual implementation, not just spec documents. Specifically:\n\n### 1. Cryptographic implementation\n- Read `crates/ember-crypto/` (or equivalent crypto crate) — check actual XEdDSA implementation, low-order point validation, nonce derivation, key zeroization\n- Check if `Zeroize`/`ZeroizeOnDrop` is used on all secret key material\n- Check UUID v4 generation — what RNG is used? Is there fallback behavior on RNG failure?\n- Check BLAKE3 KDF context strings — are they unique across all derivation sites?\n\n### 2. Wire format and parsing\n- Read `crates/ember-message/` (or equivalent message crate) — check OuterEnvelope/InnerEnvelope deserialization, size limits, error handling\n- Look for panics, unwraps, or unbounded allocations in parsing paths\n- Check tombstone verification — is `ack_hash` comparison constant-time?\n\n### 3. DAG implementation\n- Find the `ConversationDag`, `ReceiverGapDetector`, `SenderGapDetector` implementations\n- Check: is there any bound on orphan accumulation? Any eviction?\n- Check: ContentId collision handling — what happens if two messages produce the same 8-byte hash?\n- Check: epoch validation — can a peer force arbitrary epoch advances?\n\n### 4. Transport and delivery\n- Read the `TransportCoordinator` and tiered delivery implementation\n- Check: what exactly gates Direct tier success? Is it HTTP 2xx only, or is receipt validation enforced?\n- Check: retry patterns — can an observer distinguish urgent vs. distributed phase by timing?\n- Check: rate limiting implementation on mailbox nodes — per-IP, per-routing-key, what limits?\n\n### 5. Storage\n- Check SQLite usage — is WAL mode enabled? Any SQL injection vectors (unlikely with bindings, but verify)?\n- Check what's stored unencrypted at rest — are message bodies encrypted in the database or only in transit?\n\n### 6. Mailbox node\n- Read the mailbox node implementation — what does it log? What metadata does it retain?\n- Check TTL enforcement — is it clock-based? What happens with clock skew?\n- Check fetch endpoint — does it leak timing information about message availability?\n\n## Writing phase\n\nAfter research, rewrite `docs/drafts/threat-model.md` with the following structure. Preserve the existing LAN discovery section (it's good), but expand around it.\n\n### Required document structure\n\n```markdown\n# Threat Model\n\n## Trust boundaries\n\n[Diagram showing trust boundaries between: client, LAN, mailbox node, relay peer, network observer. Define the trust model for each — especially mailbox nodes (honest-but-curious? actively adversarial?)]\n\n## Adversary model\n\n[Expand from WHITEPAPER §3.2. Define concrete adversary capabilities:]\n- Passive network observer (ISP-level)\n- Active network attacker (MITM)\n- Compromised/malicious mailbox operator\n- Malicious peer (contact or stranger)\n- Endpoint compromise (device theft, malware)\n- Global passive adversary (nation-state traffic analysis)\n\n## Attack surface: Cryptographic protocol\n\n### MIK compromise blast radius\n[Analyze: what is exposed when MIK private key is compromised? All past messages (no FS in stateless mode), all future messages until rotation, sender identity via encrypted_sender after v0.7, routing key derivation enabling mailbox correlation]\n\n### Nonce reuse via RNG failure\n[Analyze: nonce = BLAKE3_KDF(message_id || recipient_MIK). UUID v4 collision or weak RNG → nonce reuse → full plaintext recovery. What is the actual RNG used in the codebase? Is there entropy validation?]\n\n### XEdDSA edge cases\n[Analyze: birational map edge cases, twist attacks on X25519 beyond the 7 low-order points, implementation-specific risks found in code review]\n\n### Key zeroization coverage\n[Report: which secret values use Zeroize? Any gaps found in code review?]\n\n## Attack surface: Wire format and parsing\n\n### Malformed envelope processing\n[Analyze: what happens with oversized fields, truncated envelopes, invalid discriminator bytes? Are there panics or unbounded allocations? Report findings from code review of deserialization paths]\n\n### Tombstone authorization bypass\n[Analyze: can an attacker generate valid-looking tombstones without ack_secret? Is ack_hash comparison constant-time? Can tombstone flooding clear legitimate messages?]\n\n## Attack surface: DAG ordering\n\n### ContentId collision attacks\n[Analyze: 8-byte ContentId, birthday bound ~2^32. Cost for a determined attacker. Impact: message substitution in DAG, false gap signals, silent message loss. Concrete attack scenario.]\n\n### DAG poisoning via crafted references\n[Analyze: malicious sender crafting prev_self/observed_heads to create false gaps, trigger unnecessary retransmissions (amplification), or disrupt epoch management]\n\n### Orphan accumulation DoS\n[Analyze: unbounded orphan growth by withholding parent messages. What's the memory cost? Is there any eviction? Report actual implementation findings.]\n\n### Epoch manipulation\n[Analyze: peer sending epoch >> current forces DAG reset. Repeated epoch advances as disruption attack. Is epoch validated? Is there rate limiting?]\n\n## Attack surface: Mailbox node\n\n### Metadata collection\n[Analyze: what a mailbox operator learns — routing key ↔ IP correlation, polling cadence, message volume, timing patterns. Quantify: how much does hour-granularity timestamp actually help when the operator sees exact submission time?]\n\n### Selective message dropping (censorship)\n[Analyze: operator drops messages for specific routing keys. Detection: client can cross-check with other mailbox nodes if quorum > 1. What quorum configuration is safe against N compromised nodes?]\n\n### Storage exhaustion\n[Analyze: cost to fill mailbox storage. TTL enforcement behavior under pressure. Eviction policy.]\n\n### Eclipse attacks\n[Analyze: attacker controls all configured mailbox nodes for a target. Can the client detect this? What's the impact — total message suppression, traffic analysis, both?]\n\n## Attack surface: Transport layer\n\n### Retry pattern fingerprinting\n[Analyze: the three-phase delivery state machine (urgent → distributed → confirmed) has distinct timing signatures. Can a network observer distinguish phases? Can they infer delivery status?]\n\n### TTL/timestamp mutability\n[Analyze: timestamp_hours and ttl_hours are intentionally unsigned/mutable for DTN relay compatibility. A relay can reduce ttl_hours to cause premature expiry (censorship), increase it to extend storage, or shift timestamp_hours to manipulate downstream TTL enforcement.]\n\n### Direct tier receipt-gating gap\n[Preserve existing analysis from current threat model §2. This is the HTTP 2xx without valid receipt issue.]\n\n## Attack surface: Metadata and traffic analysis\n\n### Routing key correlation\n[Analyze: routing_key = BLAKE3(PublicID)[0:16] is deterministic. Anyone who knows a PublicID can compute the routing key and monitor all mailbox nodes for it. Cross-mailbox correlation if same routing key appears at multiple nodes.]\n\n### Message size fingerprinting\n[Analyze: no padding in current version. Message sizes may be distinctive (especially for short texts vs. receipts vs. tombstones). What can be inferred?]\n\n### Polling pattern analysis\n[Analyze: client polling frequency and timing reveal online/offline patterns. Different clients may have characteristic polling signatures.]\n\n## Attack surface: Denial of service\n\n### Computational DoS\n[Analyze: XEdDSA signature verification cost per incoming message. Can an attacker force expensive operations with invalid but plausible envelopes? What are the rate limits?]\n\n### Tombstone flooding\n[Analyze: tombstones are 96 bytes with ack_hash verification. Can an attacker generate enough plausible tombstones to cause processing overhead? (They can't clear messages without ack_secret, but verification still costs CPU)]\n\n### Discovery spam\n[Preserve existing analysis from current threat model §3]\n\n## LAN discovery\n\n[Preserve existing §1-§6 from current threat model — these are well-written. Add cross-references to new sections where relevant.]\n\n## Residual risk summary\n\n[Table with columns: Risk | Severity (Critical/High/Medium/Low) | Likelihood | Affected versions | Planned mitigation | Status]\n\nPrioritize by severity × likelihood. Include:\n- Receipt-gating gap (High severity, exists now)\n- MIK forward secrecy gap (High severity, mitigated by v0.7)\n- ContentId collision (Medium severity, mitigated post-v1.0)\n- Metadata exposure to mailbox operator (Medium severity, no planned mitigation)\n- Orphan accumulation (Low severity, bounded by restart)\n- TTL mutability (Medium severity, no planned mitigation)\n- etc.\n```\n\n## Constraints\n\n- **Ground claims in code, not just specs.** If you say \"ack_hash comparison is constant-time,\" cite the actual code line. If you find it's NOT constant-time, flag it.\n- **Don't invent mitigations that don't exist.** If there's no orphan eviction, say so. Don't write \"mitigated by TTL-based eviction\" unless you found that code.\n- **Preserve the existing LAN discovery analysis** — it's well-written and reviewed. Integrate it into the expanded structure, don't rewrite it.\n- **Be concrete about attack costs.** \"An attacker could find a ContentId collision\" is weak. \"An attacker performing 2^32 BLAKE3 evaluations (~seconds on modern GPU) can find a ContentId collision\" is useful.\n- **Flag implementation bugs as separate issues.** If code review reveals a missing constant-time comparison, a panic in a parsing path, or a missing Zeroize derive, note it inline AND collect all bugs in a \"## Implementation findings\" appendix with file paths and line numbers.\n- **Don't bloat the document with obvious/generic threats.** \"An attacker could steal the device\" doesn't need a full section unless there's something specific to Ember's design (e.g., at-rest encryption gaps).\n- **Use the format: Attack → Mitigation → Residual risk** consistently, matching the existing LAN discovery sections.\n\n## Output\n\n1. The rewritten `docs/drafts/threat-model.md`\n2. If implementation bugs are found during research, create a separate `THREAT-MODEL-FINDINGS.md` with actionable items (file path, line number, severity, recommended fix)",
