            "content": "# Threat Model\n\nAttack scenarios, mitigations, and residual risks for the Ember messaging system.\n\nThis document covers the full protocol — cryptography, wire format, DAG ordering, transport layer, mailbox nodes, and metadata exposure. Each section follows the structure: **Attack → Mitigation → Residual risk**. Claims about code behavior cite file paths and line numbers from the v0.5 codebase.\n\n---\n\n## Trust boundaries\n\n```text\n┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│  ENDPOINT (fully trusted)                                                   │\n│  ┌──────────────┐  ┌──────────────┐  ┌───────────────┐                     │\n│  │ Private Key   │  │ Plaintext    │  │ Contact List  │                     │\n│  │ (MIK)         │  │ Messages     │  │ & DAG State   │                     │\n│  └──────────────┘  └──────────────┘  └───────────────┘                     │\n├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤\n│  TRANSPORT (untrusted — encrypted envelopes only)                           │\n│  ┌──────────────┐  ┌──────────────┐  ┌───────────────┐                     │\n│  │ LAN (mDNS)   │  │ HTTP/MQTT    │  │ BLE/LoRa      │                     │\n│  │              │  │              │  │ (future)      │                     │\n│  └──────┬───────┘  └──────┬───────┘  └───────┬───────┘                     │\n│         │                 │                   │                             │\n│  ┌──────▼───────┐  ┌──────▼───────┐  ┌───────▼───────┐                     │\n│  │ LAN Peer     │  │ Mailbox Node │  │ Relay Peer    │                     │\n│  │ (ephemeral)  │  │ (stable)     │  │ (future)      │                     │\n│  └──────────────┘  └──────────────┘  └───────────────┘                     │\n├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤\n│  NETWORK OBSERVER (passive or active — sees encrypted traffic only)         │\n└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n```\n\n**Trust model by role:**\n\n| Role | Trust level | What they see | What they can do |\n|------|------------|---------------|------------------|\n| **Client endpoint** | Fully trusted | Everything (plaintext, keys) | Anything |\n| **Mailbox node** | Honest-but-curious | Routing key, coarse timestamp, message size, client IP, polling cadence | Store/forward, potentially drop or delay messages |\n| **LAN peer** | Untrusted | Routing key (via mDNS), encrypted envelopes | Submit messages, attempt impersonation |\n| **Relay peer** (future) | Untrusted | Routing key, encrypted envelopes | Forward, drop, or delay messages |\n| **Network observer** | Adversarial | IP addresses, message timing, sizes, routing keys | Traffic analysis, active MITM on unauth'd channels |\n\n---\n\n## Adversary model\n\n### Passive network observer (ISP-level)\n\n**Capabilities:** Sees all traffic between client and mailbox nodes. Knows IP addresses, timing, message sizes, connection patterns. Cannot decrypt content.\n\n**Relevant sections:** [Retry pattern fingerprinting](#retry-pattern-fingerprinting), [Polling pattern analysis](#polling-pattern-analysis), [Message size fingerprinting](#message-size-fingerprinting).\n\n### Active network attacker (MITM)\n\n**Capabilities:** Can inject, modify, delay, drop, or replay network packets. Cannot forge E2E encrypted content or XEdDSA signatures.\n\n**Relevant sections:** [Identity challenge relay](#2-identity-challenge-relay-mitm-on-verification), [TTL/timestamp mutability](#ttltimestamp-mutability).\n\n### Compromised/malicious mailbox operator\n\n**Capabilities:** Full access to node storage and logs. Sees routing keys, exact submission timestamps, client IP addresses, message sizes, and polling patterns. Can selectively drop or delay messages.\n\n**Relevant sections:** [Metadata collection](#metadata-collection), [Selective message dropping](#selective-message-dropping), [Storage exhaustion](#storage-exhaustion), [Eclipse attacks](#eclipse-attacks).\n\n### Malicious peer (contact or stranger)\n\n**Capabilities:** Can send crafted messages — malformed envelopes, manipulated DAG fields, epoch attacks, flooding. If a contact, has a valid MIK and can produce valid signatures.\n\n**Relevant sections:** [DAG poisoning](#dag-poisoning-via-crafted-references), [Epoch manipulation](#epoch-manipulation), [Orphan accumulation DoS](#orphan-accumulation-dos), [Discovery spam](#3-discovery-spam--resource-exhaustion).\n\n### Endpoint compromise (device theft, malware)\n\n**Capabilities:** Full access to SQLite database, private key material, decrypted messages, contact list.\n\n**Relevant sections:** [MIK compromise blast radius](#mik-compromise-blast-radius), [At-rest storage](#at-rest-storage).\n\n### Global passive adversary (nation-state traffic analysis)\n\n**Capabilities:** Observes traffic across multiple mailbox nodes simultaneously. Can correlate routing keys, timing, and volume patterns globally.\n\n**Relevant sections:** [Routing key correlation](#routing-key-correlation), [Polling pattern analysis](#polling-pattern-analysis).\n\n---\n\n## Attack surface: Cryptographic protocol\n\n### MIK compromise blast radius\n\n**Attack:** An attacker obtains a user's MIK private key (device theft, malware, backup leak). In stateless encryption mode (current v0.5), the MIK is the recipient side of every ECDH exchange.\n\n**Impact:**\n\n- **All past messages** encrypted to this MIK are decryptable (no forward secrecy in stateless mode)\n- **All future messages** until the key is rotated\n- **Sender identity** exposed via `encrypted_sender` field (v0.7+) — the attacker can derive who is communicating\n- **Routing key derivation** — `routing_key = BLAKE3(PublicID)[0:16]` is computable from the PublicID, enabling mailbox monitoring for all messages to/from this identity\n- **ack_secret derivation** — the attacker can compute ack_secrets for all messages and create valid tombstones, clearing messages from relay nodes\n- **Signature forgery** — the attacker can sign messages as the compromised identity via XEdDSA\n\n**Mitigation (v0.5):** None. This is the fundamental trade-off of stateless MIK-only encryption, accepted for DTN tolerance.\n\n**Mitigation (v0.7 — planned):** Async Noise XX handshake provides per-session forward secrecy. After a session is established, compromising the MIK does not reveal past session-encrypted messages (the `ee` DH with ephemeral keys is the forward secrecy anchor — see `docs/drafts/session-encryption.md`). However, MIK compromise still allows future impersonation and decryption of any stateless-mode messages.\n\n**Residual risk:** High (v0.5). Reduced to Medium after v0.7 for messages sent within established sessions. Stateless fallback messages remain fully exposed.\n\n### Nonce reuse via RNG failure\n\n**Attack:** The encryption nonce is derived as `BLAKE3_KDF(\"ember-nonce-v0\", message_id || recipient_MIK)[0:12]` (`crates/ember-encryption/src/lib.rs:245-250`). A UUID v4 collision in `message_id` with the same `recipient_MIK` produces an identical nonce. With ChaCha20-Poly1305, nonce reuse under the same key enables XOR of two plaintexts and potential full plaintext recovery.\n\n**RNG analysis:** UUID v4 is generated via `Uuid::new_v4()` (`crates/ember-message/src/outer_envelope.rs:63`), which uses the `getrandom` crate backed by the OS entropy source (`/dev/urandom` on Linux, `BCryptGenRandom` on Windows). Ephemeral X25519 keypairs use `OsRng` (`crates/ember-encryption/src/lib.rs:80`). Both panic on failure (fail-closed — correct security posture).\n\n**Collision probability:** UUID v4 provides 122 random bits. Birthday bound at 50% collision requires ~2^61 messages — far beyond any realistic usage. The nonce itself is 96 bits derived from a 122-bit UUID, so the UUID collision is the binding constraint.\n\n**Mitigation:** Strong OS-level RNG with fail-closed behavior. No weak RNG fallbacks exist in the codebase.\n\n**Residual risk:** Negligible under normal operation. Catastrophic if the OS RNG is compromised (e.g., `/dev/urandom` on a system with insufficient entropy at boot). This is a system-level concern, not specific to Ember.\n\n### XEdDSA edge cases\n\n**Attack:** XEdDSA uses the birational map between Montgomery (X25519) and Twisted Edwards (Ed25519) curves. Edge cases include: points not on the curve, the sign bit ambiguity, and the 7 low-order points that produce predictable shared secrets.\n\n**Implementation review:**\n\n- **Low-order point validation:** All 7 known small-order points are defined in `crates/ember-identity/src/lib.rs:16-28` and validated before encryption (`crates/ember-encryption/src/lib.rs:77`) and decryption (`crates/ember-encryption/src/lib.rs:124`). Additionally, an all-zero shared secret check (`crates/ember-encryption/src/lib.rs:91,140`) catches any remaining degenerate ECDH results.\n- **Birational map:** Uses `curve25519_dalek::MontgomeryPoint::to_edwards(0)` (sign bit = 0) consistently in both signing (`crates/ember-identity/src/xeddsa.rs:43`) and verification (`crates/ember-identity/src/xeddsa.rs:73`). The `to_edwards()` return value is checked for `None` (line 77) — points that don't map to Edwards form are rejected.\n- **Strict verification:** Uses `verify_strict()` from `ed25519-dalek` (line 87), which rejects non-canonical signatures and small-order components.\n- **Deterministic nonces:** XEdDSA signing uses RFC 8032-style deterministic nonce derivation via `ed25519-dalek` internals.\n\n**Residual risk:** Low. The implementation follows established library code paths. The main risk is upstream bugs in `curve25519-dalek` or `ed25519-dalek`, which are widely reviewed.\n\n### Key zeroization coverage\n\n**Code review findings:**\n\n| Secret material | Type | Zeroized? | Location |\n|----------------|------|-----------|----------|\n| MIK private key | `IdentitySecret(StaticSecret)` | Yes (`Zeroize + ZeroizeOnDrop`) | `ember-identity/src/lib.rs:36-37` |\n| Ephemeral secret | `EphemeralSecret` | Yes (consumed by DH, implements `Zeroize`) | `ember-encryption/src/lib.rs:80` |\n| Shared secret | `SharedSecret` | Yes (implements `Zeroize`) | `ember-encryption/src/lib.rs:88,137` |\n| **Encryption key** | `[u8; 32]` | **No** — stack variable, not zeroized | `ember-encryption/src/lib.rs:95,149` |\n| **Nonce** | `[u8; 12]` | **No** — stack variable, not zeroized | `ember-encryption/src/lib.rs:97,151` |\n| **ack_secret** | `[u8; 16]` | **No** — returned as raw bytes | `ember-message/src/tombstone.rs:56-64` |\n| **BLAKE3 intermediates** | `[u8; 32]` | **No** — KDF output arrays | Multiple locations |\n\n**Residual risk:** Medium. Derived encryption keys and ack_secrets remain on the stack after use. An attacker with memory read access (core dump, cold boot attack, `/proc/mem`) could extract them. The window is small (function scope), but the keys are as sensitive as the shared secret they're derived from.\n\n---\n\n## Attack surface: Wire format and parsing\n\n### Malformed envelope processing\n\n**Attack:** An attacker submits crafted data to a mailbox node or directly to a client — oversized payloads, truncated envelopes, invalid discriminator bytes, or malformed postcard-encoded fields.\n\n**Implementation review:**\n\n- **Wire discriminator:** `WirePayload::decode()` (`crates/ember-message/src/wire.rs:51-81`) checks for empty input, reads a 1-byte discriminator, and returns `WireError::UnknownDiscriminator` for unknown values. No panics.\n- **Deserialization:** Uses `postcard::from_bytes()` which returns `Result`. All parse paths return proper `WireError::DeserializeError` — no `unwrap()` or `expect()` in any deserialization code path.\n- **Size limits:** There are **no message-layer size limits** on `inner_ciphertext` (`Vec<u8>`), `observed_heads` (`Vec<ContentId>`), or `Content::Text(String)`. The only protection is from the transport layer (Axum's default 2 MB body limit), which is **not explicitly configured** in the node code (`crates/ember-node-core/src/server.rs`).\n- **Fuzz coverage:** Fuzz harnesses exist for `WirePayload::decode`, `OuterEnvelope`, `InnerEnvelope`, and `SignedAckTombstone` deserialization (`crates/ember-message/fuzz/`).\n\n**Mitigation:** Postcard's varint-prefixed lengths bound allocations to the input data size (no amplification). Fuzz testing covers the main parse paths. No panics found in any deserialization path.\n\n**Residual risk:** Low for crashes (well fuzz-tested). Medium for resource exhaustion — a 2 MB payload containing a maximally-sized `observed_heads` vector would allocate proportionally. An explicit message-layer size limit would reduce this to negligible.\n\n### Tombstone authorization bypass\n\n**Attack:** An attacker without the ECDH shared secret attempts to create a tombstone that clears legitimate messages from a relay node.\n\n**Analysis:**\n\n- **ack_hash verification is constant-time:** `verify_authorization()` (`crates/ember-message/src/tombstone.rs:145-148`) uses `subtle::ConstantTimeEq` (`ct_eq`) — no timing side-channel.\n- **ack_secret is cryptographically bound:** Derived from `BLAKE3_KDF(\"ember-ack-v1\", shared_secret || message_id)`. Without the shared secret (requires either the sender's ephemeral private key or the recipient's MIK private key), an attacker cannot derive ack_secret.\n- **Brute-force cost:** ack_secret is 16 bytes (128 bits). Brute-forcing requires ~2^128 BLAKE3 evaluations — infeasible.\n- **Tombstone flooding:** An attacker can submit tombstones with random ack_secret values. Each requires: 1 BLAKE3 KDF (to derive ack_hash from ack_secret) + 1 constant-time comparison against stored ack_hash. Failed tombstones do not clear messages. The cost is CPU time on the node for verification — bounded by rate limiting (which currently does not exist — see [Computational DoS](#computational-dos)).\n\n**Residual risk:** Negligible for authorization bypass. Low-Medium for tombstone verification CPU cost due to missing rate limiting.\n\n---\n\n## Attack surface: DAG ordering\n\n### ContentId collision attacks\n\n**Attack:** ContentId is 8 bytes (64 bits), computed as `BLAKE3(\"ember-content-id-v1\" || sender || timestamp || content)[0:8]` (`crates/ember-message/src/content_id.rs:37-48`). Birthday bound: ~2^32 messages for 50% collision probability.\n\n**Cost:** BLAKE3 is extremely fast (~1 GB/s per core). An attacker performing 2^32 BLAKE3 evaluations needs ~4 billion hashes × ~64 bytes input ≈ ~256 GB of input data processed at ~1 GB/s ≈ **~4 minutes on a single modern core.** With a GPU, this drops to seconds.\n\n**Impact:** There is **no collision detection** in the codebase. A ContentId collision causes:\n\n1. **ReceiverGapDetector:** `complete.insert()` silently deduplicates — the second message is treated as already-known. Orphans waiting on the colliding ContentId may be falsely resolved by a different message.\n2. **SenderGapDetector:** `sent.insert()` overwrites the chain link — breaks the `prev_self` chain and corrupts `find_missing()` results.\n3. **peer_heads:** Conflates two different messages — false acknowledgments via `observed_heads`.\n\n**Practical constraint:** The attacker must be a conversation participant (only sender + timestamp + content contribute to ContentId, and the sender field is verified via signature). A third-party observer cannot inject colliding ContentIds. However, a malicious contact could craft messages with chosen content to collide with specific prior messages.\n\n**Mitigation:** None in the current implementation. The whitepaper notes \"8 bytes provides ~4 billion messages at 50% birthday collision probability — more than sufficient for any realistic use\" (`docs/merkle-dag.md`), but this analysis assumes accidental collisions, not targeted attacks.\n\n**Residual risk:** Medium. A malicious contact with modest computational resources can cause silent message loss, corrupted gap detection, or false delivery confirmations within their conversation. Expanding ContentId to 16 bytes would raise the birthday bound to ~2^64, making targeted collisions infeasible.\n\n### DAG poisoning via crafted references\n\n**Attack:** A malicious sender crafts `prev_self` and `observed_heads` to disrupt the peer's DAG state.\n\n**Scenarios:**\n\n1. **False gap signaling:** Send a message with `prev_self` pointing to a ContentId that was never sent. The receiver creates an orphan that can never be resolved, triggering retransmission requests for a message that doesn't exist.\n2. **Retransmission amplification:** By referencing ContentIds strategically, the attacker can cause the peer's outbox to schedule immediate retries for messages already delivered, wasting bandwidth.\n3. **peer_heads bloat:** Sending many messages with `prev_self = None` (without `FLAG_DETACHED`) adds entries to `peer_heads` without removing any. This bloats the `observed_heads` field in all subsequent outgoing messages.\n\n**Mitigation:** Orphans are only tracked in-memory and cleared on restart. DAG poisoning from a contact requires that contact to be added (social trust). However, there are no rate limits on DAG field manipulation.\n\n**Residual risk:** Low-Medium. Constrained to contacts only. The primary impact is resource waste (memory for orphans, bandwidth for unnecessary retransmissions). See also [Orphan accumulation DoS](#orphan-accumulation-dos).\n\n### Orphan accumulation DoS\n\n**Attack:** A malicious contact sends messages with `prev_self` referencing ContentIds that are never sent. Each such message creates an orphan entry in `ReceiverGapDetector.orphans` (`HashMap<ContentId, OrphanInfo>`) and a `waiting_on` entry (`HashMap<ContentId, Vec<ContentId>>`), neither of which has a size bound or eviction policy.\n\n**Code review:** `ReceiverGapDetector` (`crates/ember-message/src/dag.rs`) stores orphans in three unbounded data structures: `complete: HashSet<ContentId>`, `orphans: HashMap<ContentId, OrphanInfo>`, and `waiting_on: HashMap<ContentId, Vec<ContentId>>`. There is no eviction, no TTL, and no maximum size. The `SenderGapDetector.sent` (`HashMap<ContentId, Option<ContentId>>`) is similarly unbounded.\n\n**Memory cost per orphan:** ~56 bytes (8-byte ContentId key + ~48 bytes HashMap overhead). 1 million orphans ≈ 56 MB. Sustainable for a long partition but nontrivial for constrained devices.\n\n**Mitigation:** Orphans are cleared on process restart (receiver state is not persisted). The `docs/merkle-dag.md` documentation acknowledges this gap: \"A TTL-based eviction policy could prevent unbounded growth during prolonged partitions.\"\n\n**Residual risk:** Low. Bounded by process lifetime. On a continuously-running client, a malicious contact could cause gradual memory growth over days/weeks. A TTL-based eviction policy would close this gap.\n\n### Epoch manipulation\n\n**Attack:** A malicious contact sends a message with `epoch = 65535` (maximum `u16` value). The receiver processes this at `crates/ember-core/src/lib.rs:313-315`:\n\n```rust\nlet peer_epoch_advanced = inner.epoch > dag.epoch;\nif peer_epoch_advanced {\n    dag.advance_to_peer_epoch(inner.epoch);\n}\n```\n\n`advance_to_peer_epoch()` (`crates/ember-message/src/dag.rs:441-451`) resets the receiver gap detector and `peer_heads`:\n\n```rust\nself.epoch = new_epoch;\nself.receiver.clear();\nself.peer_heads.clear();\n```\n\n**Impact:**\n\n1. All receiver gap detection state is lost — previously tracked orphans and complete messages are forgotten.\n2. Subsequent legitimate messages from the real contact (at a lower epoch) are silently treated as old-epoch messages and processed without gap detection (epoch < current → `GapResult::Complete`).\n3. The local `clear_conversation_dag()` uses `wrapping_add(1)` — after a forced advance to 65535, a local clear wraps to 0, which is less than 65535, creating inconsistency.\n4. There is **no rate limiting** on epoch advances. A single malicious message is sufficient.\n\n**Mitigation:** None. Epoch advances are accepted unconditionally from any message within a conversation.\n\n**Residual risk:** High for targeted disruption. A malicious contact can permanently disrupt DAG ordering for their conversation with a single crafted message. Mitigation options: rate-limit epoch advances (e.g., max 1 per hour), require epoch advances to be monotonically incremental (not arbitrary jumps), or add an epoch confirmation round.\n\n---\n\n## Attack surface: Mailbox node\n\n### Metadata collection\n\n**Attack:** A mailbox node operator collects metadata from normal operation.\n\n**What a mailbox operator learns:**\n\n| Metadata | Source | Precision |\n|----------|--------|-----------|\n| Routing key | OuterEnvelope field | Exact (16 bytes) |\n| Client IP | TCP connection | Exact |\n| Submission time | Node's `received_at` timestamp | Exact (sub-second) |\n| Message size | OuterEnvelope byte length | Exact |\n| Polling cadence | Fetch request frequency | Exact |\n| TTL | OuterEnvelope `ttl_hours` field | Hour granularity |\n| Coarse send time | OuterEnvelope `timestamp_hours` | Hour granularity |\n\n**Note on timing:** The OuterEnvelope uses hour-granularity timestamps to limit timing analysis, but the node records exact `received_at` timestamps (`crates/ember-node-core/src/store.rs`). A compromised operator gets sub-second precision regardless of the coarse envelope timestamp.\n\n**Correlation attacks:** The operator can correlate routing keys across time to build communication profiles. If the operator serves multiple users, submit/fetch timing can link sender and recipient routing keys with high probability — especially for low-traffic routing keys where a submit is quickly followed by a fetch.\n\n**Mitigation:** Routing keys are one-way (BLAKE3 hash of PublicID) — the operator cannot derive the PublicID from the routing key. Message content is E2E encrypted. The operator cannot read, modify, or forge message content.\n\n**Residual risk:** Medium. A mailbox operator learns communication metadata (who talks to whom, when, how often, message sizes). No planned mitigation in the current architecture. Future options: cover traffic, routing key rotation, multiple mailbox nodes with different routing keys.\n\n### Selective message dropping (censorship)\n\n**Attack:** A mailbox operator drops messages for specific routing keys while serving others normally.\n\n**Detection:** If quorum > 1, a client can cross-check message availability across multiple mailbox nodes. If messages appear at node A but not node B (for the same routing key), node B may be censoring.\n\n**Quorum analysis:** With `Count(2)` quorum and 3 mailbox nodes, the sender reaches at least 2 nodes. If 1 node is compromised, the recipient still has 2 honest nodes to fetch from. With `Count(N)` and N+1 nodes, the system tolerates 1 compromised node. With `All` quorum, any single compromised node can censor.\n\n**Mitigation:** Quorum semantics ensure message redundancy across multiple nodes. The default `Any` quorum for 1-2 nodes provides no censorship resistance. `Count(2)` with 3+ nodes provides basic resistance.\n\n**Residual risk:** Medium. Depends entirely on quorum configuration. Single-node deployments have zero censorship resistance.\n\n### Storage exhaustion\n\n**Attack:** An attacker submits many large messages for the same routing key (or many routing keys), exhausting the node's storage.\n\n**Implementation review:** There are **no per-routing-key storage quotas** and **no rate limiting** on the submit endpoint (`crates/ember-node-core/src/server.rs`). The only storage control is TTL-based expiration. An attacker can submit messages faster than TTL expires them.\n\n**Cost estimate:** Axum's default body limit is 2 MB. At 100 requests/second (trivial from a single machine), the attacker can push ~200 MB/second to a node. Without rate limiting, a node with 100 GB of storage could be filled in ~8 minutes.\n\n**Mitigation:** TTL enforcement removes expired messages. The node never allocates more than the incoming envelope size per message. But without rate limiting, TTL expiration cannot keep pace with a determined attacker.\n\n**Residual risk:** High. No rate limiting means a single attacker can exhaust node storage trivially. Rate limiting (per-IP and per-routing-key) is the minimum necessary mitigation.\n\n### Eclipse attacks\n\n**Attack:** An attacker controls all configured mailbox nodes for a target user. This can happen if the attacker operates or compromises the specific nodes a user is configured to use.\n\n**Impact:**\n\n- **Total message suppression:** The attacker can drop all incoming and outgoing messages.\n- **Full traffic analysis:** The attacker sees all routing keys, timing, and sizes.\n- **No detection by the client:** The client has no mechanism to verify that a mailbox node is forwarding messages honestly. Messages appear to send successfully (HTTP 200) but are silently dropped.\n\n**Mitigation:** Users can configure multiple independent mailbox nodes operated by different parties. Quorum semantics provide redundancy if at least one node is honest.\n\n**Residual risk:** High for users relying on a single mailbox node. Medium with 3+ nodes from independent operators using `Count(2)` quorum.\n\n---\n\n## Attack surface: Transport layer\n\n### Retry pattern fingerprinting\n\n**Attack:** The three-phase delivery state machine has distinct timing signatures observable by a network monitor:\n\n- **Phase 1 (Urgent):** Exponential backoff: 5s → 10s → 20s → 40s → 60s → 60s... (configurable at `crates/ember-outbox/src/lib.rs`)\n- **Phase 2 (Distributed):** Regular 4-hour intervals\n- **Phase 1→2 transition:** Rapid retries stop, switching to infrequent maintenance\n\n**What an observer learns:**\n\n1. **Message creation time** — first retry attempt\n2. **Quorum achievement** — transition from rapid to slow retries\n3. **Direct delivery success** — retries stop entirely\n4. **Final acknowledgment** — retries cease permanently (Phase 3)\n\n**Mitigation:** None. The timing patterns are inherent to the delivery state machine design.\n\n**Residual risk:** Medium. A network observer can infer delivery status with high confidence from timing patterns. Mitigation options: jitter in retry timing, constant-rate background traffic, randomized phase transition delays.\n\n### TTL/timestamp mutability\n\n**Attack:** `timestamp_hours` and `ttl_hours` in the OuterEnvelope are not authenticated — a relay or MITM can modify them without detection.\n\n**Scenarios:**\n\n1. **TTL reduction:** A relay sets `ttl_hours` to 0, causing immediate expiry at downstream nodes. Effect: targeted message censorship.\n2. **TTL extension:** A relay increases `ttl_hours`, causing messages to persist longer than intended. Effect: increased metadata exposure window.\n3. **Timestamp manipulation:** Shifting `timestamp_hours` affects TTL enforcement at downstream nodes (since some implementations compute expiry from the envelope timestamp rather than receive time).\n\n**Mitigation:** The Ember node uses `received_at + ttl_hours` for expiry calculation (based on its own clock, not the envelope timestamp), which limits timestamp manipulation impact. However, a relay that modifies `ttl_hours` before forwarding directly affects the node's expiry calculation.\n\n**Residual risk:** Medium. TTL reduction enables censorship-by-expiry. TTL extension extends the metadata exposure window. Including TTL in authenticated (signed) data is complex because relay nodes legitimately need to adjust TTL for DTN scenarios.\n\n### Direct tier receipt-gating gap\n\n**Attack:** A relay attacker who passes identity verification (via challenge relay — see [§2](#2-identity-challenge-relay-mitm-on-verification)) returns HTTP 200 OK with an empty or invalid receipt. The Direct tier considers this a success. Quorum fallback is not triggered. The message is blackholed.\n\n**Implementation:** `try_direct_tier()` in `TransportCoordinator` considers any HTTP 2xx as success, regardless of receipt content (`crates/ember-transport/src/coordinator.rs`). Receipt signatures are verified and recorded but do **not** gate tier success.\n\n**Mitigation:** None currently. Receipts are verified but not enforced.\n\n**Residual risk:** High for targeted message suppression via LAN-based MITM. The correct fix is receipt-gated direct tier success — require a verified receipt signature for Direct tier to be considered successful.\n\n---\n\n## Attack surface: Metadata and traffic analysis\n\n### Routing key correlation\n\n**Attack:** `routing_key = BLAKE3(PublicID)[0:16]` is deterministic. Anyone who knows a user's PublicID can compute their routing key and monitor all mailbox nodes for messages addressed to it.\n\n**Cross-mailbox correlation:** If the same routing key appears at multiple mailbox nodes, an observer with visibility across nodes can confirm the user uses those nodes and observe their traffic patterns.\n\n**Contact graph inference:** When sender A submits a message with routing key R_B to a mailbox node, the node learns the edge (A's IP → R_B). If A's routing key is known (from their own polling), the operator learns the contact relationship (R_A ↔ R_B).\n\n**Mitigation:** Routing keys are one-way hashes — knowing the routing key does not reveal the PublicID. However, an attacker with a candidate PublicID can confirm it in a single BLAKE3 evaluation.\n\n**Residual risk:** Medium. Routing key stability enables long-term surveillance. Future mitigation: rotating routing keys (post-v1.0).\n\n### Message size fingerprinting\n\n**Attack:** No padding in current version. Message sizes reveal information:\n\n| Message type | Approximate size |\n|-------------|-----------------|\n| Short text (< 50 chars) | ~200 bytes |\n| Medium text (200 chars) | ~350 bytes |\n| Receipt (Delivered/Read) | ~180 bytes |\n| Tombstone | 97 bytes (1-byte discriminator + 96-byte tombstone) |\n\nAn observer can distinguish tombstones from messages, receipts from text messages, and short texts from long texts with high confidence.\n\n**Mitigation:** None. Fixed-size padding is planned for post-v1.0 (`ROADMAP.md` Future considerations → Better privacy).\n\n**Residual risk:** Medium. Size metadata is particularly useful for identifying message types (text vs receipt vs tombstone) which reveals user activity patterns (reading, typing, acknowledging).\n\n### Polling pattern analysis\n\n**Attack:** A client's fetch polling frequency and timing reveal online/offline patterns. Different clients may have characteristic polling signatures (e.g., mobile clients with battery-optimized schedules vs. desktop clients with aggressive polling).\n\n**Metadata exposed to mailbox node:** Exact timestamps of every fetch request, duration of connection, number of messages retrieved, routing key.\n\n**Mitigation:** None. Polling is the fundamental mechanism for message retrieval from mailbox nodes.\n\n**Residual risk:** Medium. A mailbox operator can build precise activity profiles for each routing key. Mitigation options: constant-rate polling (wastes bandwidth), multiple nodes with different polling schedules, push-based delivery (requires persistent connections).\n\n---\n\n## Attack surface: Denial of service\n\n### Computational DoS\n\n**Attack:** An attacker submits many invalid but plausible envelopes to a mailbox node, forcing expensive operations.\n\n**Cost per incoming message on the node:**\n\n- Deserialization: ~microseconds (postcard is fast)\n- Storage: SQLite insert with ~microseconds per row\n- No crypto operations on the node (nodes don't decrypt)\n\n**Cost per incoming tombstone:**\n\n- Deserialization: ~microseconds\n- ack_hash verification: 1 BLAKE3 KDF + 1 constant-time comparison ≈ ~nanoseconds\n- No signature verification on the node (only clients verify signatures)\n\n**For clients receiving messages:**\n\n- X25519 ECDH: ~microseconds per message\n- BLAKE3 KDF: ~nanoseconds\n- ChaCha20-Poly1305 decrypt: ~microseconds\n- XEdDSA signature verify: ~microseconds (most expensive operation)\n\n**Implementation review:** There is **no rate limiting** on any node endpoint (`crates/ember-node-core/src/server.rs`). An attacker can force unlimited deserialization, storage, and tombstone verification operations.\n\n**Residual risk:** High for node-level DoS (no rate limiting). Low for client-level computational DoS (crypto operations are cheap relative to network I/O).\n\n### Tombstone flooding\n\n**Attack:** An attacker submits tombstones with random ack_secret values, targeting messages for a specific routing key.\n\n**Analysis:** Each tombstone is 97 bytes on the wire. The node must: deserialize, look up the message by message_id, compute `BLAKE3_KDF(\"ember-ack-hash-v1\", ack_secret)`, and compare with the stored `ack_hash` using constant-time comparison. Failed tombstones do not clear messages.\n\n**Cost to attacker:** Trivial — can generate millions of tombstones per second.\n\n**Cost to node:** Each tombstone verification is ~nanoseconds (BLAKE3 + comparison), but the SQLite lookup to find the stored message is ~microseconds. Without rate limiting, a flooding attacker can cause sustained I/O pressure on the node's database.\n\n**Mitigation:** The node cannot clear messages without a valid ack_secret (128-bit brute-force resistance). But the verification CPU/I/O cost is unbounded due to missing rate limiting.\n\n**Residual risk:** Medium. Cannot cause data loss but can degrade node performance. Rate limiting on the tombstone endpoint would reduce to negligible.\n\n### Discovery spam\n\n**Attack**: Mallory floods the network with thousands of mDNS advertisements, each with a different routing key, attempting to exhaust the discovery controller's resources.\n\n**Mitigation**:\n- The controller enforces `max_peers` (default 256) independently on verified peers and the stranger cache, bounding total tracked entries at ~2x `max_peers`\n- Only peers whose routing key matches a known contact are verified and registered; strangers are cached (not verified) for later matching when new contacts are added\n- Identity verification is concurrent (JoinSet) with 2s connect / 5s total HTTP timeouts, bounding total refresh time\n- The mDNS-SD backend uses `broadcast` channels that drop events on lag rather than growing unboundedly\n\n**Residual risk**: An attacker who knows a contact's routing key (16 bytes, derived from their public key via BLAKE3) could trigger verification attempts. The configurable peer cap (default: 256, via `LanDiscoveryConfig.max_peers`) and the HTTP timeouts bound the amplification. Strangers are cached without verification — a flooding attacker can fill the stranger cache with fake entries, but the cache is bounded by `max_peers` and entries are never used for message delivery (only for triggering verification when a contact is later added).\n\n---\n\n## Attack surface: At-rest storage\n\n### Unencrypted client database\n\n**Attack:** An attacker with filesystem access (device theft, malware, forensic extraction) reads the SQLite database.\n\n**Implementation review:** The client stores all data in an **unencrypted SQLite database** (`crates/ember-storage/src/lib.rs`). WAL mode is enabled for performance. No SQLCipher or equivalent encryption.\n\n**What is stored unencrypted:**\n\n- **MIK private key** — full compromise of identity\n- **Plaintext message bodies** — all conversation history\n- **Contact list** — PublicIDs and display names\n- **DAG state** — conversation ordering metadata\n- **Outbox entries** — including serialized OuterEnvelope bytes and InnerEnvelope bytes\n\n**Mitigation:** None. No at-rest encryption exists.\n\n**Residual risk:** Critical. Device compromise exposes everything. SQLCipher (or OS-level full-disk encryption) is the standard mitigation.\n\n---\n\n## LAN Discovery\n\n### 1. Impersonation via mDNS routing key spoofing\n\n**Attack**: Mallory advertises herself on mDNS with Bob's routing key (`rk=<Bob's RK>`). Alice's discovery controller matches the routing key against her contact list and attempts to register Mallory as Bob's direct transport target.\n\n**Mitigation**: The discovery controller performs identity verification before registering any target. It sends a random challenge to the discovered peer's `/api/v1/identity` endpoint and verifies the XEdDSA signature against known contact public keys. Mallory cannot produce a valid signature without Bob's private key. The peer is silently ignored if verification fails.\n\n**Residual risk**: None — Mallory is never registered as a target.\n\n### 2. Identity challenge relay (MITM on verification)\n\n**Attack**: Mallory advertises Bob's routing key, intercepts Alice's identity challenge, forwards it to the real Bob, and replays Bob's signed response back to Alice. Alice now believes Mallory is Bob and registers her as a direct target.\n\n**Mitigation**: Even if Mallory passes verification, the transport layer limits the impact:\n\n1. **Confidentiality**: Messages are E2E encrypted to Bob's MIK (X25519). Mallory cannot decrypt them.\n2. **If Mallory proxies to Bob**: She is acting as a relay — the message reaches Bob and the system works as designed. This is functionally equivalent to the relay architecture the system already supports.\n\n**Known gap — receipt-gated direct tier**: Currently, `try_direct_tier()` considers any HTTP 2xx response as success, regardless of receipt validity. The receipt signature (XEdDSA over domain-separated `signer_pubkey || message_id`) is verified and recorded but does **not** gate tier success. This means:\n\n- **If Mallory returns 200 with no/invalid receipt**: The direct tier succeeds, the message is blackholed, and quorum fallback is **not** triggered.\n- **If Mallory drops the connection**: HTTP error → direct tier fails → quorum fallback works correctly.\n\n<!-- TODO: Implement receipt-gated direct tier success — require a verified receipt -->\n<!-- signature (or at minimum ack_secret presence) for Direct tier to be considered -->\n<!-- successful. Without this, a relay attacker returning 200 OK can silently -->\n<!-- blackhole messages. See threat model §2. -->\n\n**Residual risk**: A relay attacker who passes identity verification can silently drop messages by returning HTTP 200 with an empty/invalid receipt. Mallory also learns that Alice (by her IP address) is attempting to send to Bob's routing key — this reveals a contact-graph edge (Alice → Bob) beyond what mDNS broadcasts expose, since the advertisement shows Bob's presence but not which clients are interested in it.\n\n**Why channel binding was deferred**: An earlier design included channel binding (mixing the responder's IP:port into the challenge hash). Even with channel binding, the receipt-gating gap above would still allow message blackholing. The correct fix is receipt-gated direct tier success, not channel binding. Channel binding may be revisited once receipt-gated tiers are implemented. See PR #87 close rationale.\n\n### 3. Discovery spam / resource exhaustion\n\n**Attack**: Mallory floods the network with thousands of mDNS advertisements, each with a different routing key, attempting to exhaust the discovery controller's resources.\n\n**Mitigation**:\n- The controller enforces `max_peers` (default 256) independently on verified peers and the stranger cache, bounding total tracked entries at ~2x `max_peers`\n- Only peers whose routing key matches a known contact are verified and registered; strangers are cached (not verified) for later matching when new contacts are added\n- Identity verification is concurrent (JoinSet) with 2s connect / 5s total HTTP timeouts, bounding total refresh time\n- The mDNS-SD backend uses `broadcast` channels that drop events on lag rather than growing unboundedly\n\n**Residual risk**: An attacker who knows a contact's routing key (16 bytes, derived from their public key via BLAKE3) could trigger verification attempts. The configurable peer cap (default: 256, via `LanDiscoveryConfig.max_peers`) and the HTTP timeouts bound the amplification. Strangers are cached without verification — a flooding attacker can fill the stranger cache with fake entries, but the cache is bounded by `max_peers` and entries are never used for message delivery (only for triggering verification when a contact is later added).\n\n### 4. Stale peer targets after network change\n\n**Attack**: Not an adversarial attack, but a reliability concern. A peer goes offline without sending an mDNS goodbye packet (e.g., abrupt network disconnect). The controller retains the stale target, and direct-tier delivery attempts fail until the mDNS TTL expires.\n\n**Mitigation**:\n- The HTTP target's circuit breaker marks the target as unhealthy after 2 consecutive failures (ephemeral threshold), with 10s recovery window\n- Unhealthy targets are skipped by the coordinator's target selection\n- Direct tier has a configurable timeout; failure falls back to quorum\n- When the mDNS daemon detects the service is gone (TTL expiry), it emits `PeerLost` and the controller removes the target\n- On controller shutdown, all tracked peers are deregistered from the coordinator\n\n**Residual risk**: Brief window (seconds) of failed direct delivery before circuit breaker trips. Quorum fallback ensures delivery.\n\n### 5. Routing key privacy leakage\n\n**Attack**: An observer on the LAN can see routing keys in mDNS TXT records. Since `routing_key = BLAKE3(PublicID)[..16]`, this is a 16-byte truncated hash of the peer's public identity. An attacker who knows a target's PublicID can confirm their presence on the network.\n\n**Mitigation**:\n- Routing keys are one-way (BLAKE3 hash) — knowing the routing key does not reveal the PublicID\n- However, an attacker with a candidate PublicID can compute `BLAKE3(candidate)[..16]` and check for a match\n- This is inherent to the mDNS discovery model — advertising presence on the LAN necessarily reveals some identity information\n\n**Residual risk**: Presence confirmation for targeted surveillance. Acceptable for the LAN-first threat model. Future mitigation options include rotating routing keys or using ephemeral advertisement identifiers.\n\n### 6. Fetch polling privacy (why ephemeral targets are SEND-only)\n\n**Attack**: If Alice polls an mDNS-discovered peer for messages (`GET /api/v1/fetch/{routing_key}`), she reveals her own routing key to that peer. A malicious peer could collect routing keys of all clients polling it.\n\n**Mitigation**: Ephemeral targets (discovered via mDNS) default to `TargetCapabilities { send: true, fetch: false, .. }`. The capability-filtered fetch path skips targets without the `fetch` capability. Alice never polls discovered peers — she only sends to them. Message fetching happens exclusively from trusted stable mailbox nodes.\n\n**Residual risk**: None — the capability system prevents this by design.\n\n---\n\n## Residual risk summary\n\n| Risk | Severity | Likelihood | Affected versions | Planned mitigation | Status |\n|------|----------|-----------|-------------------|-------------------|--------|\n| Unencrypted client database (MIK + plaintext) | **Critical** | Medium (requires device access) | All | SQLCipher or OS-level FDE | Not started |\n| No rate limiting on node endpoints | **High** | High (trivial to exploit) | All | Per-IP and per-routing-key rate limiting | Not started |\n| Receipt-gating gap (Direct tier) | **High** | Medium (requires LAN MITM) | All | Receipt-gated Direct tier success | Not started (#90) |\n| Epoch manipulation by malicious contact | **High** | Low (requires contact relationship) | All | Rate-limit/validate epoch advances | Not started |\n| MIK forward secrecy gap | **High** | Medium (MIK compromise) | ≤ v0.6 | Async Noise XX (v0.7) | Planned |\n| Node storage exhaustion | **High** | High (no rate limiting) | All | Rate limiting + per-routing-key quotas | Not started |\n| Mailbox operator metadata collection | **Medium** | Certain (inherent to architecture) | All | None planned (architectural trade-off) | Accepted |\n| Retry pattern fingerprinting | **Medium** | Medium (requires traffic observation) | All | Jitter, cover traffic | Not planned |\n| Routing key correlation | **Medium** | Medium (requires PublicID knowledge) | All | Routing key rotation (post-v1.0) | Future |\n| Message size fingerprinting | **Medium** | Medium (requires traffic observation) | All | Fixed-size padding (post-v1.0) | Future |\n| TTL/timestamp mutability by relays | **Medium** | Low (requires relay position) | All | Include in authenticated data (complex) | Not planned |\n| ContentId collision (targeted) | **Medium** | Low (requires contact + 2^32 compute) | All | Expand to 16 bytes (post-v1.0) | Future |\n| Encryption key not zeroized on stack | **Medium** | Low (requires memory access) | All | Wrap in Zeroizing<> type | Not started |\n| Unbounded orphan accumulation | **Low** | Low (bounded by restart) | All | TTL-based orphan eviction | Not started |\n| peer_heads bloat from malicious sender | **Low** | Low (requires contact) | All | Cap peer_heads size | Not started |\n| Tombstone flooding CPU cost | **Low** | Medium (no rate limiting) | All | Rate limiting on tombstone endpoint | Not started |\n\n---\n\n## Implementation findings\n\nCode issues discovered during this threat model review are tracked in `THREAT-MODEL-FINDINGS.md`.\n",
