            "content": "# Threat Model Implementation Findings\n\nActionable issues discovered during the threat model review of the v0.5 codebase (2026-03-31). Organized by severity.\n\n---\n\n## Critical\n\n### F1. Unencrypted client database\n\n**Location:** `crates/ember-storage/src/lib.rs`\n\n**Issue:** The client's SQLite database is stored as a plain unencrypted file. Contains MIK private key, plaintext message bodies, contact list, DAG state, and outbox entries including serialized envelope bytes.\n\n**Impact:** Device compromise (theft, malware, forensic extraction) exposes the user's entire identity and message history.\n\n**Recommended fix:** Integrate SQLCipher for at-rest encryption. Derive the database key from a user-provided passphrase or OS keychain. At minimum, document that users should rely on OS-level full-disk encryption.\n\n---\n\n## High\n\n### F2. No rate limiting on mailbox node endpoints\n\n**Location:** `crates/ember-node-core/src/server.rs`\n\n**Issue:** The submit (`POST /api/v1/submit`), fetch (`GET /api/v1/fetch/:routing_key`), and identity (`GET /api/v1/identity`) endpoints have no rate limiting. Searched for `rate_limit`, `RateLimit`, `throttle`, `governor`, `tower::limit` — none found.\n\n**Impact:** A single attacker can exhaust node storage (submit flooding), cause CPU/IO pressure (tombstone flooding), or degrade service quality (fetch flooding). At Axum's default 2 MB body limit and 100 req/s, an attacker can push ~200 MB/s to a node.\n\n**Recommended fix:** Add `tower::RateLimitLayer` or `governor` middleware with:\n- Per-IP rate limits (e.g., 10 req/s for submit, 20 req/s for fetch)\n- Per-routing-key submit limits (e.g., 100 messages/hour per routing key)\n- Global request ceiling\n\n### F3. No explicit HTTP body size limit\n\n**Location:** `crates/ember-node-core/src/server.rs`\n\n**Issue:** No `DefaultBodyLimit` configured for the Axum server. Relies on Axum's default (2 MB), which is not documented and could change.\n\n**Impact:** An unexpectedly large payload could cause significant memory allocation.\n\n**Recommended fix:** Add explicit `DefaultBodyLimit::max(MAX_ENVELOPE_SIZE)` to the Axum router, where `MAX_ENVELOPE_SIZE` is a protocol-documented constant.\n\n### F4. Epoch manipulation has no validation or rate limiting\n\n**Location:** `crates/ember-core/src/lib.rs:313-315`, `crates/ember-message/src/dag.rs:441-451`\n\n**Issue:** A message with `epoch > dag.epoch` unconditionally triggers `advance_to_peer_epoch()`, which resets the receiver gap detector and peer_heads. No rate limiting, no sanity checking, no maximum jump size. A single message with `epoch = 65535` permanently disrupts DAG ordering for that conversation.\n\n**Impact:** A malicious contact can reset all receiver state with one message. Subsequent legitimate messages (at lower epoch) are silently processed without gap detection.\n\n**Recommended fix (options):**\n1. Require epoch advances to be monotonically incremental (`new_epoch == current_epoch + 1`)\n2. Rate-limit epoch advances (e.g., max 1 per hour per contact)\n3. Add a confirmation round — advance only after seeing 2+ messages at the new epoch\n4. At minimum, log a warning on epoch jumps > 1\n\n---\n\n## Medium\n\n### F5. Derived encryption key not zeroized\n\n**Location:** `crates/ember-encryption/src/lib.rs:95,149`\n\n**Issue:** The 32-byte encryption key (`enc_key: [u8; 32]`) derived from the BLAKE3 KDF is stored as a stack variable and not zeroized after use. The Rust compiler may optimize away a simple zeroing write.\n\n**Impact:** The key remains in memory until the stack frame is reused. An attacker with memory read access (core dump, cold boot, `/proc/mem`) can extract it.\n\n**Recommended fix:** Wrap in `zeroize::Zeroizing<[u8; 32]>`, which guarantees zeroization on drop:\n```rust\nlet enc_key = Zeroizing::new(derive_encryption_key(...));\n```\n\n### F6. ack_secret not zeroized\n\n**Location:** `crates/ember-message/src/tombstone.rs` — `derive_ack_secret()` returns `[u8; 16]`\n\n**Issue:** The ack_secret is derived and returned as a raw byte array. Callers receive it as a plain `[u8; 16]` with no zeroization mechanism. The BLAKE3 intermediate `[u8; 32]` hash is also not zeroized.\n\n**Impact:** Similar to F5 — ack_secret exposure allows creating valid tombstones, clearing messages from relay nodes.\n\n**Recommended fix:** Return `Zeroizing<[u8; 16]>` from `derive_ack_secret()`.\n\n### F7. No per-routing-key storage quota on mailbox node\n\n**Location:** `crates/ember-node-core/src/store.rs`\n\n**Issue:** No limit on how many messages can be stored for a single routing key. The only storage control is TTL-based expiration.\n\n**Impact:** An attacker can target a specific routing key with unlimited message submissions, consuming disproportionate storage and potentially causing eviction of other users' messages (once global storage limits are hit, if any).\n\n**Recommended fix:** Add a per-routing-key message count limit (e.g., 1000 messages) with oldest-first eviction.\n\n### F8. No message-layer size limits\n\n**Location:** `crates/ember-message/src/outer_envelope.rs`, `crates/ember-message/src/inner_envelope.rs`\n\n**Issue:** No explicit size limits on `inner_ciphertext: Vec<u8>`, `observed_heads: Vec<ContentId>`, or `Content::Text(String)` at the message layer. Size is bounded only by the transport layer.\n\n**Impact:** A crafted message with a very large `observed_heads` vector would cause proportional memory allocation during deserialization and processing.\n\n**Recommended fix:** Add message-layer constants for maximum sizes:\n- `MAX_INNER_CIPHERTEXT_SIZE: usize = 65536`\n- `MAX_OBSERVED_HEADS: usize = 64`\n- `MAX_TEXT_SIZE: usize = 65536`\nValidate during deserialization and reject messages exceeding limits.\n\n### F9. Unbounded orphan accumulation in ReceiverGapDetector\n\n**Location:** `crates/ember-message/src/dag.rs` — `ReceiverGapDetector`\n\n**Issue:** `orphans`, `waiting_on`, and `complete` data structures grow without bound. No eviction policy, no TTL, no maximum size. Acknowledged in `docs/merkle-dag.md` as a known gap.\n\n**Impact:** A malicious contact can cause unbounded memory growth by sending messages referencing never-sent ContentIds. ~56 bytes per orphan entry.\n\n**Recommended fix:** Add TTL-based eviction (e.g., orphans older than 1 hour are evicted) and a maximum orphan count (e.g., 10,000). On eviction, use `mark_complete()` as an escape hatch for orphans that will never resolve.\n\n---\n\n## Low\n\n### F10. Nonce not zeroized\n\n**Location:** `crates/ember-encryption/src/lib.rs:97,151`\n\n**Issue:** The 12-byte nonce `[u8; 12]` is not zeroized after use. Nonce leakage is less critical than key leakage (the nonce is derived from public inputs: message_id + recipient_pub), but defense-in-depth suggests zeroizing it.\n\n**Recommended fix:** Wrap in `Zeroizing<[u8; 12]>` for consistency.\n\n### F11. BLAKE3 KDF intermediates not zeroized\n\n**Location:** Multiple — all `blake3::derive_key()` call sites\n\n**Issue:** The full 32-byte BLAKE3 output is used to extract shorter values (16 bytes for ack_secret, 12 bytes for nonce), but the intermediate 32-byte array is not zeroized. The unused bytes may contain sensitive key material.\n\n**Recommended fix:** Wrap BLAKE3 output in `Zeroizing<[u8; 32]>` before truncation.\n\n### F12. Unbounded SenderGapDetector.sent growth\n\n**Location:** `crates/ember-message/src/dag.rs` — `SenderGapDetector`\n\n**Issue:** The `sent: HashMap<ContentId, Option<ContentId>>` tracks every message sent in a conversation, growing linearly without bound. Not persisted (cleared on restart), but long-running clients with active conversations will accumulate large maps.\n\n**Impact:** Gradual memory growth. For a very active conversation (thousands of messages), this could reach megabytes.\n\n**Recommended fix:** Prune entries older than some threshold (e.g., entries whose ContentId has been confirmed by the peer via `observed_heads`). Alternatively, cap the map size and evict oldest entries.\n\n---\n\n## Informational (no fix needed)\n\n### I1. Uuid::new_v4 panics on RNG failure\n\n**Location:** `crates/ember-message/src/outer_envelope.rs:63`\n\n**Issue:** `Uuid::new_v4()` (via `getrandom`) panics if the OS entropy source is unavailable.\n\n**Assessment:** This is the correct fail-closed behavior. The alternative (returning an error or using a weak fallback) would be worse. The OS entropy source being unavailable is an extreme edge case (very early boot on some Linux kernels).\n\n### I2. Low-order point check uses standard equality\n\n**Location:** `crates/ember-identity/src/lib.rs:30-34`\n\n**Issue:** `is_low_order_point()` uses standard `==` comparison (not constant-time) when checking public keys against the 7 low-order points.\n\n**Assessment:** Public keys are not secret. The timing difference reveals only whether a submitted public key is one of 7 well-known points, which is not security-relevant information. No fix needed.\n\n### I3. Tombstone ack_hash comparison is already constant-time\n\n**Location:** `crates/ember-message/src/tombstone.rs:145-148`\n\n**Assessment:** Uses `subtle::ConstantTimeEq` (`ct_eq`). This is correct.\n",
