eer that continuously sends messages where each references a never-arriving parent can grow `orphans` without limit (lines 96–107). Each such message costs two heap allocations (one `HashMap` insert into `orphans`, one `Vec` push into `waiting_on`).\n\nThere is no eviction policy. Orphans are only removed when their parent arrives (`try_resolve_orphans`, line 169) or when `clear()` is called on an epoch increment. There is no TTL on `OrphanInfo.received_at_ms` that would trigger automatic pruning — the timestamp is recorded (line 39) but nothing acts on it.\n\n### Orphan chain resolution — iterative, not recursive\n\nThe `try_resolve_orphans` method (lines 169–188) is **iterative** using an explicit `work_queue: Vec<ContentId>`. A chain of N stacked orphans that all resolve at once will use O(N) heap for `work_queue` and `resolved`, but will not overflow the call stack. This is correctly implemented.\n\nHowever, the O(N) work-queue expansion is itself a DoS vector: if an attacker pre-stages 100,000 orphaned messages each linked in a single chain, the arrival of the root triggers processing all 100,000 in one synchronous blocking call inside the `Mutex` lock at line 306 of `crates/ember-core/src/lib.rs`. This holds the `dag_state` mutex for the entire resolution pass.\n\n---\n\n## 3. SenderGapDetector\n\n**File:** `crates/ember-message/src/dag.rs`, lines 198–360\n\n### Data structures\n\n| Field | Type | Role |\n|---|---|---|\n| `sent` | `HashMap<ContentId, Option<ContentId>>` | All sent messages, keyed by content_id |\n| `heads` | `HashSet<ContentId>` | Current leaf nodes (heads) of sent DAG |\n\n### No bound on sent messages\n\n`sent` grows with every outgoing message and is never pruned (no eviction). The comment at line 213 notes multi-head support for multi-device forks. In a long-running session, this map accumulates all sent messages indefinitely in memory.\n\n### `find_missing` — time complexity analysis\n\n`find_missing` (lines 265–285) has two code paths:\n\n1. `peer_observed.is_empty()` → calls `all_sent_ordered()` (lines 293–311): O(N) DFS traversal of `sent`. Benign if called rarely.\n\n2. Otherwise calls `messages_not_seen()` (lines 316–339):\n   - First pass: walk ancestors of all `peer_observed` entries. In the worst case traverses all N messages in `sent`. O(N).\n   - Second pass: scan all keys of `sent` to find non-ancestors. O(N).\n   - Sort result: O(K log K) where K = missing count.\n\nIf a peer sends a crafted `observed_heads` containing a single bogus ID (not present in `sent`), it hits the `seen.is_empty()` branch (line 278) and falls back to `all_sent_ordered()`, returning the full history. This is O(N) both in time and in the size of the returned `Vec`.\n\nIf the attacker calls this path repeatedly (e.g., by sending messages with bogus `observed_heads`), they trigger O(N) allocation and DFS traversal per received message, where N is the total lifetime sent-message count. This becomes more expensive as the conversation grows.\n\n---\n\n## 4. ContentId Collision Handling\n\n**File:** `crates/ember-message/src/lib.rs`, lines 93–101 and 253–275\n\n`ContentId` is `[u8; 8]` — 64 bits. Hash input is `\"ember-content-id-v1\" || PublicID (32 bytes) || created_at_ms (8 bytes) || serialized_content`. BLAKE3 truncated to 64 bits.\n\nBirthday bound for collisions: ~2^32 ≈ 4 billion messages per per-sender namespace (since `PublicID` is part of the hash input). The comment at line 94 acknowledges this: \"Birthday bound ~4 billion messages.\"\n\n### No collision detection\n\nThere is no guard anywhere that checks for a duplicate `ContentId` being inserted into `ReceiverGapDetector.complete`, `SenderGapDetector.sent`, or `ConversationDag.peer_heads`. Both `HashSet::insert` and `HashMap::insert` silently overwrite on collision.\n\n**Impact of a collision:**\n\n- **`ReceiverGapDetector.complete`:** If message B has the same `ContentId` as already-complete message A, `complete.insert(content_id)` is a no-op (already present). Any children of B waiting for its ID via `waiting_on` will be resolved, potentially incorrectly treating B's orphaned children as complete even if their true parent is missing.\n\n- **`ReceiverGapDetector.orphans` / `waiting_on`:** If two distinct messages hash to the same `ContentId`, the second `orphans.insert` (line 96) silently replaces the first entry. The first orphan's `missing_parent` is lost; the `waiting_on` entry for the first's parent still contains the `ContentId`, but when resolved it will look up against the second orphan's metadata.\n\n- **`SenderGapDetector.sent`:** `sent.insert(content_id, prev_self)` (line 236) silently overwrites. The `heads` `HashSet` is also updated based on the overwritten data. This corrupts the sender's chain pointer, potentially creating a broken DAG reference.\n\n- **`peer_heads`:** `peer_heads.insert(content_id)` at lines 466–467. Collision would incorrectly merge two distinct peer messages into one tracked head, losing one entry from the peer head set.\n\nNo collision is realistically expected in honest usage, but a malicious peer who can choose their own `PublicID` and `created_at_ms` could in principle search for a collision against a known target `ContentId` in ~2^32 operations (birthday), which is within reach for a determined attacker in 2026.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Epoch Validation\n\n**File:** `crates/ember-core/src/lib.rs`, lines 312–316; `crates/ember-message/src/dag.rs`, lines 426–451\n\n### How epoch is validated on receive\n\n```rust\n// lib.rs line 313\nlet peer_epoch_advanced = inner.epoch > dag.epoch;\nif peer_epoch_advanced {\n    dag.advance_to_peer_epoch(inner.epoch);\n}\n```\n\nThis is the **only epoch check**. Any authenticated peer can send a message with `epoch = 65535` (max `u16`) and the receiver will:\n1. Accept it immediately (no rate limit, no sanity check)\n2. Call `advance_to_peer_epoch(65535)`, which clears `receiver`, `peer_heads`, and sets `epoch = 65535`\n\n**Forced epoch advance is a DoS 