owever:\n\n- **Multi-device / forks:** If a peer uses N devices and never merges branches, `peer_heads` grows to N entries and stays there indefinitely. There is no cap on N.\n\n- **Adversarial scenario:** A peer can artificially create fork growth by sending messages where each new message cites a parent that was already removed from `peer_heads` (because it had already been superseded). In practice the `remove(&parent)` call is a no-op when the parent is no longer a head, so `peer_heads` only grows — it shrinks only when a parent that is currently a head is superseded. A peer sending detached messages (`prev_self = None`, no flag) would grow `peer_heads` by 1 per message without limit, since each inserts a new head and no parent is removed.\n\nSpecifically: `update_peer_heads` is called for complete messages only (line 333–337). A flood of complete detached messages (all with `prev_self = None`) from a single peer causes one insert per message into `peer_heads` with zero removes, growing it without bound.\n\nThe persisted `peer_heads` blob in `dag_state` (storage line 464: `peer_heads.concat()`) would also grow proportionally, causing unbounded SQLite writes per message.\n\n---\n\n## Summary Table\n\n| Finding | Location | Severity |\n|---|---|---|\n| Orphan accumulation unbounded — no max size, no TTL eviction | `dag.rs:96–107` | High DoS |\n| Bulk orphan resolution holds mutex for O(N) duration | `dag.rs:169–188`, `lib.rs:306` | Medium DoS |\n| `SenderGapDetector.sent` grows without bound | `dag.rs:236` | Medium DoS |\n| `find_missing` O(N) triggered by unknown `observed_heads` | `dag.rs:265–285` | Medium DoS |\n| Peer can force arbitrary epoch advance, clearing all receiver state | `lib.rs:313–315` | High |\n| Epoch overflow (u16 wrapping) not handled — parties desynchronize at epoch 65535 | `dag.rs:427`, `dag.rs:441–447` | Medium |\n| `debug_assert` in `advance_to_peer_epoch` is a no-op in release builds | `dag.rs:442–447` | Low |\n| No ContentId collision detection anywhere in DAG tracking | `lib.rs:101`, `dag.rs:84,96,123,236,462` | Low (currently), escalates at scale |\n| `peer_heads` grows unbounded under detached-message flood or multi-device | `dag.rs:461–468` | Medium DoS |\n| Epoch regression silently ignored — orphan accumulation from cross-epoch refs | `lib.rs:313`, `dag.rs:897` | Low/Info |\n| `dag_state` HashMap has no cap on number of conversations (contacts) | `lib.rs:141, 310` | Low DoS |</result>\n<usage><total_tokens>73144</total_tokens><tool_uses>18</tool_uses><duration_ms>111150</duration_ms></usage>\n</task-notification>",
