            "file_path": "/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/THREAT-MODEL-FINDINGS.md",
            "new_string": "### F2. Rate limiter trusts X-Forwarded-For without proxy allowlist\n\n**Location:** `apps/node/src/rate_limit.rs` — `SmartIpKeyExtractor`\n\n**Issue:** The per-IP rate limiter (tower-governor) uses `SmartIpKeyExtractor` which honors the `X-Forwarded-For` header. Without a trusted reverse proxy, an attacker can trivially bypass per-IP rate limits by spoofing this header. No configuration option exists to restrict XFF trust to a known proxy CIDR.\n\n**Impact:** Per-IP rate limits (10 submit/s, 20 fetch/s) are ineffective when the node is directly exposed to the internet without a reverse proxy.\n\n**Recommended fix:** Add a `trusted_proxy_cidrs` configuration option. Only honor `X-Forwarded-For` from trusted proxy IPs. When empty, always use the direct connection IP.\n\n### F3. No global node-wide rate limit\n\n**Location:** `apps/node/src/rate_limit.rs`, `apps/node/src/api.rs`\n\n**Issue:** Rate limiting exists per-IP and per-routing-key, but there is no global node-wide request cap. An attacker using many IPs (or spoofing XFF) and many routing keys can bypass both limits simultaneously.\n\n**Impact:** Coordinated multi-source flooding can overwhelm the node's storage, CPU, or network capacity despite per-key/per-IP limits being in place.\n\n**Recommended fix:** Add a global token bucket (e.g., `governor::Quota::per_second(1000)`) as outer middleware before per-IP/per-key checks.\n\n### F3a. Sender-controlled TTL with no server-side cap\n\n**Location:** `crates/ember-node-core/src/mailbox_store.rs:668-675`\n\n**Issue:** The node trusts the sender's `ttl_hours` value from the OuterEnvelope with no upper-bound cap. A malicious sender can set `ttl_hours = 65535` (~7.5 years), creating near-permanent storage entries. The `default_ttl_secs` config is only used when `ttl_hours` is absent. `TOMBSTONE_MAX_AGE_HOURS` is declared but not enforced.\n\n**Impact:** Fills per-mailbox quota (1000 messages) with extremely long-lived entries, causing legitimate messages to be rejected with \"mailbox full\".\n\n**Recommended fix:** Add `max_ttl_hours` server-side config (e.g., 168 hours / 1 week). Clamp incoming `ttl_hours` to `min(envelope.ttl_hours, config.max_ttl_hours)`.",
            "old_string": "### F2. No rate limiting on mailbox node endpoints\n\n**Location:** `crates/ember-node-core/src/server.rs`\n\n**Issue:** The submit (`POST /api/v1/submit`), fetch (`GET /api/v1/fetch/:routing_key`), and identity (`GET /api/v1/identity`) endpoints have no rate limiting. Searched for `rate_limit`, `RateLimit`, `throttle`, `governor`, `tower::limit` — none found.\n\n**Impact:** A single attacker can exhaust node storage (submit flooding), cause CPU/IO pressure (tombstone flooding), or degrade service quality (fetch flooding). At Axum's default 2 MB body limit and 100 req/s, an attacker can push ~200 MB/s to a node.\n\n**Recommended fix:** Add `tower::RateLimitLayer` or `governor` middleware with:\n- Per-IP rate limits (e.g., 10 req/s for submit, 20 req/s for fetch)\n- Per-routing-key submit limits (e.g., 100 messages/hour per routing key)\n- Global request ceiling\n\n### F3. No explicit HTTP body size limit\n\n**Location:** `crates/ember-node-core/src/server.rs`\n\n**Issue:** No `DefaultBodyLimit` configured for the Axum server. Relies on Axum's default (2 MB), which is not documented and could change.\n\n**Impact:** An unexpectedly large payload could cause significant memory allocation.\n\n**Recommended fix:** Add explicit `DefaultBodyLimit::max(MAX_ENVELOPE_SIZE)` to the Axum router, where `MAX_ENVELOPE_SIZE` is a protocol-documented constant.",
