            "new_string": "### F10. Client SQLite database does not enable WAL mode\n\n**Location:** `crates/ember-storage/src/lib.rs:107-130`\n\n**Issue:** The client-side `Storage::open()` does not set `PRAGMA journal_mode=WAL`. The node-side `PersistentMailboxStore` correctly enables WAL (`crates/ember-node-core/src/mailbox_store.rs:222-237`). This discrepancy means the client database has worse crash-recovery semantics and lower concurrent read performance.\n\n**Recommended fix:** Add `PRAGMA journal_mode=WAL; PRAGMA synchronous=NORMAL;` to `Storage::open()` initialization.\n\n### F11. ContentId uses plain hash mode, not BLAKE3 KDF\n\n**Location:** `crates/ember-message/src/lib.rs:254-274`\n\n**Issue:** `InnerEnvelope::content_id` uses `blake3::Hasher::new()` (plain hash mode) and manually prepends `b\"ember-content-id-v1\"` as data input. This does NOT use BLAKE3's `new_derive_key()`, which provides cryptographically stronger domain separation via a separate initial hash value. For a content-addressed ID (non-secret input), this is acceptable, but it deviates from the pattern used by all other BLAKE3 derivation sites in the codebase.\n\n**Recommended fix:** Switch to `blake3::Hasher::new_derive_key(\"ember-content-id-v1\")` for consistency and stronger domain separation.\n\n### F12. Nonce not zeroized",
